          "isCorrect": false,
          "prompt": "A small timeline with the CSS bar ending before the HTML download finishes."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": "One visitor reports that a site never reaches the server, while another reports a page that loads but shows a missing image. Network logs show the first visitor has no DNS answer; the second received HTML and an image request returned 404.",
      "question": "Which diagnosis fits both reports?",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "The first failure occurs during hostname resolution, before a server connection. The second gets far enough to receive HTML, but the image path is missing on the server, so the two failures are at different lifecycle stages.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "The first is a DNS problem; the second is a missing resource response."
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Both reports cannot be explained by DNS: the second visitor received HTML and an HTTP 404 for the image, proving that DNS and connection setup succeeded.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Both problems are caused by TLS negotiation."
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A parsing problem would occur after content was downloaded. The first visitor has not reached that stage, and the second has a server response specifically identifying a missing image path.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Both problems are caused by browser rendering."
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The first visitor lacks a DNS answer, so no HTTP request can reach the server. The second did make an HTTP request and received a response, so the evidence points to different stages.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Both problems are caused by a slow download."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}

